66075-110.
(2)Institute of Health Sciences, Federal University of Pará, Av. Augusto Corrêa, 
01, Belém, Pará, Brazil 66075-110.

Parkinson's disease (PD) occurs in approximately 1% of the population over 65 
years of age and has become increasingly more common with advances in age. The 
number of individuals older than 60 years has been increasing in modern 
societies, as well as life expectancy in developing countries; therefore, PD may 
pose an impact on the economic, social, and health structures of these 
countries. Oxidative stress is highlighted as an important factor in the genesis 
of PD, involving several enzymes and signaling molecules in the underlying 
mechanisms of the disease. This review presents updated data on the involvement 
of oxidative stress in the disease, as well as the use of antioxidant 
supplements in its therapy.

